# Workflow Orchestration Boundary

Use this rule when a user action triggers multiple dependent domain side effects.

## When to create a workflow service

Create a dedicated backend workflow service when a flow includes two or more of:

- state change on one aggregate/entity
- cascading updates on related entities
- task status transitions
- event-log/audit side effects
- refresh/projection rebuild requirements

## Placement and boundaries

- Implement orchestration in `backend/app/features/**/service.py` (or a focused `workflow` submodule).
- Keep routers transport-thin (auth, parsing, delegation, HTTP mapping).
- Do not orchestrate business workflows in frontend components.

## Coordination pattern (UI <-> server)

- UI sends one intent command to a workflow endpoint.
- Server executes the full workflow in one transaction where possible.
- Endpoint returns updated domain/projection state.
- UI refreshes dependent panels from server state (no client-only business truth).

## Reliability defaults

- Make workflow commands idempotent when feasible.
- Keep explicit conflict/error semantics (`422` for rule violation, `409` for conflicts).
- Persist workflow markers/events when completion state must survive reloads.
